        "text": "*[Bug 19074] parallel::makeCluster(&lt;cluster&gt;, type = \"PSOCK\") does not give an error*\n<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=19074>\n\n--- Comment #2 from Henrik Bengtsson (<mailto:henrikb@braju.com|henrikb@braju.com>) ---\nThanks for this deep dive - and sorry for not being more explicit. Yes, it's an\ncoincidence that we happens to get a new valid cluster from that incorrect\ncall. Another example is:\n\n```\n&gt; cl &lt;- parallel::makeCluster(raw(2))\n&gt; print(cl)\nsocket cluster with 2 nodes on host '00'\n```\n\nI don't think we want to gatekeep it already in `makeCluster()`, because we\ncannot predict what additional cluster `type`:s exist out there, or will be\nadded in the future. There might be valid cases where the specification are not\nthe common ones that we already know of.\n\nI suspect this is the reason for why argument `spec` is documented in very\nbroad terms;\n\n    spec: A specification appropriate to the type of cluster.\n\nInstead, I think it should be up to each cluster type to check for valid `spec`\nand `...` input, e.g. `parallel::makePSOCKcluster()` and\n`parallel::makeForkCluster()`.  So, in this case it's\n`parallel::makePSOCKcluster()` that needs to be patched.",
        "username": "r-bugs notifier",
        "icons": {
            "emoji": ":robot_face:"
        },
        "type": "message",
